(259, 1, '2014-06-17 13:58:04', '2014-06-17 13:58:04', 'Grass should be present along crop edges, especially those bordering watercourses. For the maximum amount filtration to occur, the plants must be dense and established15 to 20cm (6-8 inches) sod-forming vegetation that uniformly covers at least 90% of a square-meter plot. Grass species can be sown, but you can also allow the plants to establish themselves. However, there may be a risk of weed influx if this is done in a crop.\r\n\r\nThe width of a vegetated buffer is measured from the crop to the water source (measured from the sediment bed, usually the edge of the water). It is recommended that vegetated buffers (including grassy headlands/strips) should be about 5-10 meters in width for water filtration to occur. However this width is dependent on the crop (potatoes for example require a larger width compared to less intensive crops such as corn) as well as how steep the land issteeper land requires more coverage as rainwater may form gullies and rivulets. More information about buffer width can be found in the <a href="http://localhost/farming/?page_id=263"><strong>Setback section</strong><span style="color: #ff0000;">.</span></a>', 'Grassy Strips & Buffers', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'grassy-strips-buffers', '', '', '2014-06-17 14:07:39', '2014-06-17 14:07:39', '', 240, 'http://localhost/farming/?page_id=259', 0, 'page', '', 0),
